subSection.paragraph:
A
comprehensive metabolomic analysis enables the screening of hundreds of metabolites in an untargeted manner, contributing thus significantly to the authentication of the final products and the identification of novel polar metabolites (
Farag and Wessjohann, 2012
; 
Sarrou et al., 2018
; 
Scotti et al., 2019
; 
Agapouda et al., 2019
). Only a few studies of 

Hypericum

taxa have assumed a metabolomic approach or even the monitoring of the most abundant and medicinally important metabolites (
Porzel et al., 2014
; 
Zorzetto et al., 2015
; 
Cirak et al., 2016
), whereas limited studies have combined GC–MS and LC–MS analysis in parallel (
Helmja et al., 2011
; 
Seger et al., 2004
). Furthermore, metabolomic analysis attributes chemotaxonomic value (
Radulovic et al., 2010
; 
Crockett and Robson, 2011
; 
Cirak et al., 2016
).

Characterization of plant germplasm using molecular techniques plays an increasingly important role in the management and identification of plant genetic resources, since DNA is not affected by the environment and the developmental stage of the plant, as morphological characters usually do (
Baenziger et al., 2014
). The nuclear ribosomal internal transcribed spacer (nrITS) region or a part of it (ITS2) is one of the most frequently used nuclear markers for the identification and the phylogenetic reconstructions at the species level or even below (Li et al., 2011; 
Cheng et al., 2016
). So far, the nrITS region has been used for inferring phylogenies (
Meseguer et al., 2013
; 
Nurk et al., 2013
) and for species authentication in the genus 

Hypericum

(
Costa et al., 2016
; 
Raclariu et al., 2017
).

In 

H. triquetrifolium

essential oil, the number of compounds in traces was high and only a few were in high percentages (
Table 1
). Thus, (

E

)– 
β
–caryophyllene accounted for 27.90% and caryophyllene oxide for 15.74% of the total peak area; values higher than those in previous studies of its populations in 
Greece
and abroad (
Bertoli et al., 2003
; 
Petrakis et al., 2005
; 
Hosni et al., 2011
; 
Sajjadi et al., 2015
). In contrast, 
α
–pinene, 
n
–nonane and 2–methyl–octane that have been previously found in high quantities (
Bertoli et al., 2003
; 
Petrakis et al., 2005
; 
Hosni et al., 2007
) were in very low percentages herein.

Phenolic acids, flavonoids, naphthodianthrones and phloroglucinols were quantified in all extracts with HPLC–DAD, on a C–18 column, with a method previously developed and validated (
Zeliou et al., 2017
). The HPLC analysis was performed on an HPLC – DAD Dionex Ultimate 3000 system ( Thermo Scientific, USA ). The injection volume was 20 μL. Data were collected, stored and integrated with Chromeleon v 6.80 Systems software. HPLC analysis was performed on a C18 column (Luna C18; 250 × 4.6 mm , i. d.: 5 μm; LC Column Phenomenex, USA) set at 30 °C with a coupled guard column cartridge C18 (4 × 3.0 mm, i. d.: 5 μm; LC Column Phenomenex, USA), using ammonium acetate (pH 4.5; 10 mM)–acetonitrile–methanol in a combination of gradient and isocratic steps.

Twenty grams (
20 g
) of plant material (branches were excluded) were subjected to hydrodistillation using a Clevenger apparatus. The sample 2L flask was filled with tap water (1 L) and the distillation lasted 3 h. The essential oil was collected with the addition of 2 mL of diethyl ether, was dried over sodium sulfate, was filtrated using cellulose filter paper, and finally the solvent was removed under nitrogen flow. The oil was kept at −20 °C at a nitrogen atmosphere until use. The procedure was performed twice for each sample.

The essential oils’ components with a peak area percentage higher than 1.0% as well as the main polar metabolites of the methanolic extracts were analyzed using principal component analysis (
PCA
) (followed by Varimax rotation with Kaiser normalization) with SPSS version 23.0 (IBM Corp., Armonk, NY, 
USA
). The variables were standardized for a normalized 
PCA
; the value of 0.05 was used for compounds that could not be quantified and the value of 0.001 for compounds that were not detected. For essential oils, a matrix was created with 47 variables × 8 samples = 376 data, while for methanolic extracts, the matrix was generated from 24 variables × 8 samples = 192 data. Each component value of the Loading Plot graph was calculated in relation to the other, adjusting each value for the mean of each extraction. Biplots were produced with CATPCA (IBM Corp., Armonk, NY, 
USA
).

Two different Mantel tests (Diniz Filho et al., 2013) were conducted with PopTools version 3.2.5 (
Hood, 2011
) with 99 iterations; one for the comparison of matrices from the genetic and volatile analyses, and one for the comparison of matrices obtained from the genetic and methanolic extract analyses.
